      "content": "We need to identify a workaround conditions. Please ensure the `ulimit` settings in your Docker configuration are not hitting maximum allowed values, which might cause panics. Try running the containers with user namespaces and control groups to isolate and limit resource usage. Use `crictl config-system memory` to reassign memory cgroups priorities. Check for any conflicting services with `netstat -tulpn| grep docker` and stop them if necessary. You can also try enforcing the use of a specific CPU queue with the `--cpu-shares=20` option to balance container CPU utilization. If your dev environment has any complex networking needs, consider using a minimal base image with network utils installed only. For a possible temporary quick-fix, switch to a console to manually inspect the actual container processes using `docker ps -a` right before it crashes and log the outputs, which might contain critical error messages or clues about the malfunction. If none of these steps stabilize your environment, I would strongly advise using an external debug through live CD, preserving your configs and data while preparing your machine for additional diagnostics.",
